IMPORTANT: This License Agreement governs your use of the Trustwise CLI tool,
including all binary artifacts, runtime libraries, plugins, configuration
files, documentation, and related materials (the "CLI Tool"). By downloading,
installing, or using the CLI Tool, you accept this Agreement. If you do not
agree, do not use the CLI Tool.

================================================================================

1. DEFINITIONS
================================================================================

"CLI Tool" means the Trustwise command-line application and all associated
binary artifacts, runtime libraries, plugins, templates, and documentation
distributed by Trustwise.

"Internal Components" means the compiled binaries, object code, algorithms,
data structures, models, weights, and underlying architecture of the CLI Tool.

"Authorized Environment" means any computing environment operated by or on
behalf of You, including but not limited to local workstations, cloud virtual
machines, containers, CI/CD runners (e.g., GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, Jenkins,
CircleCI), and ephemeral build environments.

"Automation Artifacts" means scripts, configuration files, Dockerfiles, CI/CD
pipeline definitions, Makefiles, and similar files that invoke or reference the
CLI Tool.

"You" (or "Your") means the individual or legal entity exercising rights under
this Agreement.

================================================================================

2. LICENSE GRANT
================================================================================

2.1 CLI Usage Rights

Subject to this Agreement, Trustwise grants You a limited, non-exclusive,
non-transferable, royalty-free license to:

  (a) Install and execute the CLI Tool on any Authorized Environment;

  (b) Invoke CLI Tool commands from scripts, pipelines, automation tools, and
      other software;

  (c) Create Automation Artifacts that reference, call, or orchestrate the
      CLI Tool, and distribute such Automation Artifacts freely, including in
      open-source repositories;

  (d) Use CLI Tool output (reports, scores, classifications, logs) without
      restriction in Your own products, documentation, and compliance records.

2.2 No License to Internal Components

This Agreement does NOT grant any right to access, modify, or distribute the
Internal Components except as necessarily executed through normal invocation of
the CLI Tool's documented commands and flags.

================================================================================

3. RESTRICTIONS
================================================================================

3.1 Reverse Engineering Prohibition

You may NOT, and may not permit any third party to:

  (a) Reverse engineer, decompile, disassemble, or otherwise attempt to derive
      the source code, algorithms, data structures, or underlying architecture
      of the Internal Components;

  (b) Use automated tools to extract, scrape, harvest, or mine data, models,
      weights, or parameters from the Internal Components;

  (c) Circumvent, disable, or interfere with any license key, access control,
      usage tracking, obfuscation, or metering mechanism in the CLI Tool.

This prohibition applies to the fullest extent permitted by applicable law.
Where applicable law grants a non-waivable right to decompile for
interoperability purposes (e.g., EU Software Directive, Article 6), such
decompilation is permitted solely to the extent required to achieve
interoperability with independently created software, provided You first
request interoperability information from Trustwise and Trustwise has not made
such information readily available.

3.2 General Restrictions

You may NOT:

  (a) Redistribute the CLI Tool binary or runtime files as a standalone
      download, package, or toolkit separate from an Authorized Environment
      under Your control;

  (b) Use the CLI Tool to develop any product or service that competes with
      the CLI Tool itself or Trustwise's core platform;

  (c) Sublicense, lease, rent, loan, sell, or assign the CLI Tool or any
      rights therein to a third party, except that You may permit Your
      contractors, consultants, and managed service providers to execute the
      CLI Tool solely on Your behalf and under Your account;

  (d) Remove, alter, or obscure any proprietary notices, labels, or watermarks;

  (e) Bundle the CLI Tool binary inside a container image, installer, or
      archive that is published to a public registry or download site;
      however, You may build private container images that include the CLI
      Tool for use within Your Authorized Environments.

3.3 What Is Permitted

For clarity, the following activities are expressly permitted:

  (a) Installing the CLI Tool on ephemeral CI/CD runners, cloud VMs,
      containers, and other transient compute environments;

  (b) Writing and sharing shell scripts, Dockerfiles, GitHub Actions
      workflows, Makefiles, and pipeline configurations that invoke CLI Tool
      commands, including in public and open-source repositories;

  (c) Using the CLI Tool as a step in automated testing, red-teaming,
      risk-classification, and compliance pipelines;

  (d) Profiling and benchmarking the CLI Tool's performance and publishing
      such benchmarks provided they are accurate and conducted in good faith;

  (e) Examining and using CLI Tool output, logs, error messages, and
      diagnostic information without restriction;

  (f) Referencing CLI Tool commands, flags, and usage patterns in public
      documentation, blog posts, and technical discussions.

